    "heading": "Fleet Version Control: Keeping the Team Pinned to Compatible Versions",
    "body": "Claude Code installs globally via npm (`npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`). The update behavior after install depends on how users manage their Node environment — and the defaults are inconsistent enough to cause silent version drift across a team.\n\n### The Version Drift Problem\n\nVersion drift matters because managed settings keys, feature flags, and API behaviors change across minor releases. A developer on v2.1.30 and one on v2.1.149 may behave differently under the same managed policy:\n- `allowAllClaudeAiMcps` requires v2.1.149+\n- The `forceRemoteSettingsRefresh` auth-command exemption requires v2.1.139+\n- Teams managed settings require v2.1.38+\n- Enterprise managed settings require v2.1.30+\n\n### Three Version-Control Settings\n\nClaude Code provides three distinct keys for version management:\n\n| Setting | Scope | Effect |\n|---|---|---|\n| `minimumVersion` | Any scope | Prevents background auto-updates and `claude update` from installing below this version. Does NOT block startup. |\n| `requiredMinimumVersion` | Managed only | Blocks startup and exits if the running version is older. `claude update`, `claude install`, and `claude doctor` still run so users can self-remediate. |\n| `requiredMaximumVersion` | Managed only | Blocks startup and exits if the running version is newer. Background auto-updates and `claude update` skip versions above the ceiling. |\n\nFor hard enforcement — refusing to start outside an approved range — use the managed-only keys:\n\n```json\n// managed-settings.json (or admin console)\n{\n  \"requiredMinimumVersion\": \"2.1.140\",\n  \"requiredMaximumVersion\": \"2.1.200\"\n}\n```\n\n`requiredMinimumVersion` and `requiredMaximumVersion` are managed-only settings; placing them in user or project `settings.json` files has no effect.\n\n### Pinning Strategy for Enterprise\n\nA practical pattern:\n1. Set `requiredMinimumVersion` to the last version your QA process validated.\n2. Set `requiredMaximumVersion` to the same version or a range you have tested.\n3. When validating a new release, update both keys in the admin console (server-managed) or your MDM plist/file.\n4. Developers on non-compliant versions see a startup error with the version they need.\n\nFor cloud-provider deployments without server-managed settings, distribute version requirements through `managed-settings.json` via Ansible, Chef, or your package manager:\n\n```bash\n# /etc/claude-code/managed-settings.json (Linux fleet)\n{\n  \"requiredMinimumVersion\": \"2.1.140\"\n}\n```\n\n### Monitoring Version Distribution\n\nThere is no built-in fleet version dashboard outside the Claude.ai analytics for Teams/Enterprise. For cloud-provider or Console deployments, consider a `SessionStart` hook that emits version telemetry to your observability stack:\n\n```json\n// managed-settings.json\n{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"SessionStart\": [\n      {\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"curl -sf -X POST https://telemetry.internal/claude-version -d '{\\\"host\\\":\\\"'$(hostname)'\\\"}'\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n(`SessionStart` fires when a new session begins or resumes; it is a supported hook event. The version is available as part of the session's environment context.)\n\nThis gives you a live map of version distribution without requiring MDM inventory.",
    "sources": [
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/server-managed-settings",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/admin-setup"
    ]
