   {
    "heading": "Skills and Hooks: Distributing Team Procedures and Policy Enforcement",
    "body": "Skills and hooks serve complementary roles in a shared Claude Code setup. Skills are model-invocable procedures that standardize how the team does recurring work. Hooks are deterministic shell commands that fire on lifecycle events regardless of what the model decides. Neither is a substitute for the other.\n\n## Skills: Team Procedures as Code\n\n### Anatomy of a Skill\n\nEvery skill is a directory with a `SKILL.md` file:\n\n```\n.claude/skills/run-pr-checks/\n├── SKILL.md       # required\n└── checklist.md   # optional supporting file referenced from SKILL.md\n```\n\n```yaml\n# .claude/skills/run-pr-checks/SKILL.md\n---\nname: PR Checks\ndescription: Run the full PR readiness checklist before opening a pull request. Use when the user asks to prepare a PR, open a PR, or check if code is ready to review.\ndisable-model-invocation: false\nallowed-tools: Bash(npm run *) Bash(git status) Bash(git diff *)\n---\n\nRun the following in order and report any failures:\n\n1. `npm run lint` — must exit 0\n2. `npm test` — must exit 0, no skipped tests\n3. `git diff --stat HEAD` — summarize changed files\n4. Check for TODO/FIXME/HACK comments in changed files\n5. Verify no secrets in diff: `git diff HEAD | grep -iE 'password|secret|api_key'`\n\nIf all checks pass, summarize what changed and suggest a PR title.\nIf any check fails, stop and report the failure clearly.\n```\n\nThis skill is checked into the project. Every developer who clones the repo and runs `claude` gets `/run-pr-checks` available without any individual setup.\n\n### Frontmatter Fields That Matter for Team Distribution\n\n| Field | Effect | Team use case |\n|---|---|---|\n| `description` | Controls when Claude auto-invokes the skill; combined with `when_to_use`, truncated at 1,536 characters | Make specific enough that Claude doesn't invoke it accidentally |\n| `disable-model-invocation: true` | Only human can invoke via `/name`; Claude cannot trigger it; also prevents preloading into subagents | Destructive actions: deploy, send-notification, merge-branch |\n| `user-invocable: false` | Hidden from `/` menu; Claude invokes it automatically only | Background knowledge: legacy-system-context, architecture-notes |\n| `allowed-tools` | Pre-approves specific tool calls while skill is active (space- or comma-separated) | Avoids per-call prompts for well-understood tool patterns |\n| `context: fork` | Runs skill in a forked subagent context | Isolation for tasks that should not affect main session state |\n| `paths` | Skill auto-loads only when working with matching files (glob patterns) | Package-specific conventions in a monorepo |\n\n### Skill Precedence Across Levels\n\nWhen skills share the same name, enterprise overrides personal, and personal overrides project. A project-level `code-review` skill replaces the bundled `/code-review`. For monorepos with per-package skills:\n\n```\n# Both exist:\n.claude/skills/deploy/SKILL.md                  # → /deploy (project root)\napps/web/.claude/skills/deploy/SKILL.md          # → /apps/web:deploy (qualified name)\n```\n\nClaude picks the variant that matches the files it is currently working on. Users can invoke the specific variant by the qualified name.\n\n### Skill Content Lifecycle\n\nSkill **descriptions** (plus the `when_to_use` field, if set) are always in context so Claude knows what is available. These are truncated at 1,536 characters combined. The full **skill body** loads only when the skill is invoked, and once loaded it stays in context across turns — so every line is a recurring token cost. This makes skills the correct home for long reference material and step-by-step procedures.\n\n```\nCLAUDE.md:  \"Always run npm run lint before committing.\"\n            → Always in context, short\n\n.claude/skills/lint-fixer/SKILL.md:\n            → Full 150-line guide to fixing lint errors, categorized by error type\n            → Only in context when someone invokes /lint-fixer or Claude determines it is relevant\n```\n\n## Hooks: Deterministic Policy Enforcement\n\nHooks are shell commands registered to fire on lifecycle events. They run regardless of what the model decides, making them the correct mechanism for non-negotiable invariants — audit logging, pre-commit validation, tool usage recording, blocking unauthorized actions.\n\n### Hook Events\n\n```json\n// .claude/settings.json (project-level, checked in)\n{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PreToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Bash\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"/usr/local/bin/audit-bash.sh\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ],\n    \"PostToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Edit|Write\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"/usr/local/bin/record-edit.sh\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nA `PreToolUse` hook that exits with code 2 **blocks the tool call** before permission rules even run — this takes precedence over allow rules. A hook that exits 0 allows the call to proceed to permission evaluation. Deny and ask rules are still evaluated regardless of what a `PreToolUse` hook returns: a matching deny rule blocks the call, and a matching ask rule still prompts even when the hook returned allow.\n\n### Hook Precedence and `allowManagedHooksOnly`\n\nProject-level hooks in `.claude/settings.json` are active by default. If you want to ensure only managed hooks run (no developer-added hooks that could bypass audit):\n\n```json\n// managed-settings.json (managed only)\n{\n  \"allowManagedHooksOnly\": true\n}\n```\n\nWith `allowManagedHooksOnly: true`, only hooks from managed settings, SDK hooks, and hooks from plugins force-enabled in managed settings load. User and project hooks are blocked. This is a managed-only key — setting it in user or project settings has no effect.\n\n### Skills vs. Hooks: Decision Rule\n\n| Situation | Use | Reason |\n|---|---|---|\n| Step-by-step procedure a developer invokes | Skill | Model-orchestrated, contextual, on-demand |\n| Organizational knowledge that should inform Claude's decisions | Skill (`user-invocable: false`) | Loads on relevance, not every session |\n| Audit log every file edit | Hook (PostToolUse) | Fires deterministically, cannot be skipped by model |\n| Block specific commands from ever running | Permission deny rule + Hook (PreToolUse) | Defense in depth |\n| Reformat code after every write | Hook (PostToolUse) | Deterministic, independent of model decision |\n| \"Always run tests before committing\" | Hook (PreToolUse on `Bash(git commit *)`) | Enforces the policy; a CLAUDE.md instruction would only guide |\n\n### Distributing Hooks and Skills via Git\n\nChecking `.claude/settings.json` (hooks) and `.claude/skills/` (skills) into the repository is the distribution mechanism. Every clone gets the same hooks and skills without any individual configuration step. Developers can add personal hooks in `~/.claude/settings.json` or personal skills in `~/.claude/skills/` without affecting the shared project configuration — unless `allowManagedHooksOnly` or `strictPluginOnlyCustomization` is set to lock down those surfaces.",
    "sources": [
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/skills",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permissions",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/server-managed-settings",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/memory"
    ]
   },
   {
    "heading": "Bootstrap Sequence: Putting It All Together for a New Team",
    "body": "A concrete ordered sequence for a team lead standing up shared Claude Code infrastructure from scratch.\n\n### Phase 1: Choose the Deployment Path (Day 0, before any installs)\n\n1. Decide provider: Claude for Teams/Enterprise if you want the full feature set and server-managed policy; cloud provider if you have existing compliance infrastructure.\n2. If Teams/Enterprise: subscribe, configure SSO/SCIM if on Enterprise, invite team members from the admin dashboard.\n3. If cloud provider: provision IAM roles (Bedrock) or service accounts (Vertex), write env var distribution plan.\n\n### Phase 2: Author Managed Policy (Before Developer Installs)\n\nDraft your `managed-settings.json` (or admin console config for server-managed) before anyone installs:\n\n```json\n// Baseline managed policy for a typical engineering team\n{\n  \"requiredMinimumVersion\": \"2.1.140\",\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"deny\": [\n      \"Read(./.env)\",\n      \"Read(./.env.*)\",\n      \"Read(./secrets/**)\"\n    ],\n    \"disableBypassPermissionsMode\": \"disable\"\n  },\n  \"allowManagedPermissionRulesOnly\": true,\n  \"allowManagedHooksOnly\": false\n}\n```\n\nStart permissive on hooks so project-level hooks in `.claude/settings.json` work. Tighten after you understand your team's hook usage.\n\n### Phase 3: Set Up Per-Repo Artifacts (PR to each major repo)\n\n```bash\n# In each repository:\ntouch CLAUDE.md\nmkdir -p .claude/skills\ntouch .claude/settings.json\n\n# Add to .gitignore:\necho \"CLAUDE.local.md\" >> .gitignore\necho \".claude/settings.local.json\" >> .gitignore\n```\n\nMinimum `CLAUDE.md`: build commands, test commands, one-paragraph architecture summary.\n\nMinimum `.claude/settings.json`:\n```json\n{\n  \"$schema\": \"https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json\",\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"allow\": [\n      \"Bash(npm run *)\",\n      \"Bash(git status)\",\n      \"Bash(git diff *)\",\n      \"Bash(git log *)\"\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Phase 4: Author First Skills\n\nStart with the three highest-ROI skills: PR preparation checklist, commit message generator, and debugging procedure. Check into `.claude/skills/`. Run `claude` in the repo and verify `/skill-name` invocation works.\n\n### Phase 5: Non-Interactive Auth for CI\n\nFor each CI system:\n```bash\n# One-time: generate token with a service account\nclaude setup-token\n# Store output in secrets manager (Vault, GitHub Secrets, etc.)\n\n# CI pipeline environment:\nexport CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN=${{ secrets.CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN }}\nclaude -p \"$PROMPT\" --output-format json\n```\n\nFor cloud-provider deployments, use `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` from Console instead.\n\n### Phase 6: Version Pin\n\nAdd to managed policy:\n```json\n{\n  \"requiredMinimumVersion\": \"<current-stable-version>\"\n}\n```\n\nSet a calendar reminder to review and update this quarterly or when a release fixes a security issue.\n\n### Verification Checklist\n\n```bash\n# Developer runs after install:\nclaude\n/status      # Verify which auth method is active, which managed settings source\n/permissions # Verify managed deny rules are present\n# Type /run-pr-checks (or your skill name) — verify skill loads\n```\n\nThe `/status` output shows a `Setting sources` line in the format `Enterprise managed settings (remote)` for server-managed, or with `(plist)`, `(HKLM)`, `(HKCU)`, or `(file)` in parentheses for the respective endpoint-managed delivery mechanism. If the line is absent, managed settings are not being received.",
    "sources": [
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/admin-setup",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/authentication",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings",
     "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/server-managed-settings"
    ]
   }
